Macedonians will vote for the referendum if they want to change the country's name
On Sunday, Macedonian citizens voted in a referendum if they wanted the country's name to be changed to the "Northern Republic of Macedonia", a change that would resolve an old dispute with Greece, which opposed its accession to the European Union and NATO.
Greece, which comprises a province called Macedonia, claims that the name of the neighbouring country represents a claim on its territory and opposed its accession to the EU and NATO.
The two governments agreed in June on the proposed new name, but the opposition nationalists argue that this change would undermine the ethnic identity of the Slavic majority population in Macedonia.
President Gjorge Ivanov said that he would not vote in the referendum and that a boycott campaign doubted the presence of the vote, and that the minimum limit of 50% could not be reached, necessary for the validation of the referendum.
The question from the referendum ballot will be: "Do you agree with EU and NATO membership, accepting the agreement with Greece?".
Supporters of the change of name, including Prime Minister Zoran Zaev, state that it is a price to be paid by Macedonia, one of the countries that resulted from the overthrow of Yugoslavia, in order to be accepted in entities such as the EU and NATO.
"I am here today to vote for the future of the country, so that young people in Macedonia live freely under the umbrella of the European Union, because it means safer lives for all of us," Olivera Georgijevska, 79 years old, told Skopje.
Although it is not legally mandatory, quite a few members of parliament have said they will respect the outcome of the vote in order to make it decisive.
For the name to be changed, a two-thirds quorum is required in parliament.
The state's election committee said there were no irregular reports until 1 p.m.
However, the participation was only 16%, compared to 34% in the last parliamentary elections in 2016 when 66% of the voting people were put to the vote.
"We have come to the vote for my children and for our place in Europe," said a 62-year-old voter from Skopje, the capital of the country, Gjose Tanevski.
On 30 September 2018, Macedonian Prime Minister Zoran Zaev, his wife Zorica and their son Dushko voted for the referendum on the change of the name of Macedonia, which will allow him to join NATO and enter the European Union.
In front of the parliament in Skopje, Vladimir Kavardarkov, 54 years old, prepared a small stage and pulled seats in front of the tents raised by those who would boycott the referendum.
"We support NATO and the EU, but we want to join them with the top, not the back door," said Kavadarkov.
"We are a poor country, but we have dignity.
If we are not wanted by the name of Macedonia, we can go to other countries, such as China and Russia and become part of the Euro-Asian Union."
Prime Minister Zaev said accession to NATO would bring the necessary investments in Macedonia, which has a unemployment rate of more than 20%.
"I believe that most will be in favour of a change of name, because more than 80% of our citizens are in favour of accession to NATO and the EU," Zaev said after he expressed his vote.
He said that one result in favour of changing the name would be "confirming our future."
According to a poll published last month by the Policy Research Institute, between 30% and 43% of voting citizens will participate in the referendum, under the required number of participants.
According to another survey conducted by Telma TV in Macedonia, 57% of respondents plan to vote on Sunday.
Of these, 70% said they would vote in favour of change.
For the referendum to be valid, the presence of the vote must be 50% plus one vote.
The failure of the referendum would be the first serious blow to pro-vestic government policy since taking over the government last May.
