The method involves the extraction of immune cells from a patient, their alteration in the laboratory so that they can "detect" a protein common to many cancers, called HER2, then reinject the cells.
Professor Jay Berzofsky of the U.S. National Institute of Oncology in Bethesda, Maryland, said: "Our results suggest that we are dealing with a very promising vaccine."
