Foreign buyers will apply a higher rate of stamp judicial fee to purchase a property in the United Kingdom, and additional money will be used to help homeless people, as announced today by Theresa May.
The change will be considered an attempt to neutralize Jeremy Corbyn's successful efforts to attract young people with the right to vote, promising more expensive homes and targeting people with higher incomes.
The higher tax on stamps will be applied to natural and legal persons who are not paying taxes and taxes in the United Kingdom, and the additional money obtained thus will be used to support government efforts to help homeless people.
The surplus, which adds to the current tax on stamps, including the high levels two years ago for the second property and properties purchased for rent, could reach a value of 3%.
The Treasury expects this change to bring up to £120 million a year.
About 13% of new properties built in London are purchased by non-residents in the United Kingdom, which leads to price increases and makes it difficult for those who want to buy their first home.
Several prosperous areas in the country, especially in the capital, have become "ghost cities" because of the high number of foreign buyers spending much of their time outside the country.
The new policy has only come a few weeks since Boris Johnson called for a reduction in the tax on stamps to help young people buy their first home.
He accused the large construction companies of maintaining high prices on property as a result of the acquisition of land without using them and asked Thersa May to waive the fees for affordable houses, with a view to solving the UK 'home problem'.
Corbyn has announced a number of proposals for attractive real estate reforms, including rent controls and the cessation of unmotivated evacuations.
It also wishes to provide the Councils with greater powers in terms of building new houses.
Theresa May said: “Last year I said I would dedicate my prime mandate to the fulfillment of the British dream, a better life for every new generation.
And that means to remedy the problems in the real estate market.
Britain will always be open to people who want to live, work and build a life here.
However, it is not fair for people who do not live in the United Kingdom, as well as companies with headquarters abroad, to be able to buy homes as easily as British residents who work hard.
For too many people, the dream of owning a house has become one too far away, and living in unworthy conditions is too real."
Jack Ross: "My final goal is to be the manager of Scotland's national team"
Jack Ross, the manager of the Sunderland football team, said that "his final goal" is to become, at some point, the manager of Scotland's national team.
The 42-year-old Scotsman enjoys the challenge of "reviving" the Northeast Club, which is currently in place 3 in the First League, with a three-point difference from the first place.
He moved this summer to the Light Stadium team after he succeeded, last season, the return of the St. Mirren football team to the first Scottish Premiership division.
"I wanted to be a member of the national football team, but as a player.
We arrived on the B team of the national and about that," Ross told the BBC of Scotland for Sportsound.
"But I spent a lot of my childhood watching Scotland's matches at Hampden with my father and I always wanted to come back.
But I will only take this opportunity if I succeed as the club manager."
Ross' predecessors, as managers of the Sunderland Club, include Dick Advvocat, David Moyes, Sam Allardyce, Martin O'Neill, Roy Keane, Gus Poyet and Paulo Di Canio.
The former manager of the Alloa Athletic club said he has no emotions to be the successor of such consecrated names and to such an important club after he refused offers from Barnsley and Ipswich Town.
"The only thing that concerns me and that could affect my success is the question "Can I help this team get back into the Premier League?"
There is no doubt that the structure and facilities in this club allow it to be in the Premier League," he said.
"It's not easy to make her get there, but I think the only thing that would make me feel like a successful man is to contribute to the return of the club to the Premier League."
Ross has only three years of experience in leadership, after a time when he was assistant manager at Dumbarton and another 15 months spent as a member of the Hearts training staff.
Then he helped the Alloa club recover after it regraded into division C and managed to save St. Mirren from retrograde, helping the team win the title of the champion in the next season.
Ross said he feels better now than in his entire career as a player at Clyde, Hartlepool, Falkirk, St. Mirren and Hamilton Academical.
"It was a turning point," he said about taking over the Alloa club.
“I really thought my role as manager was more appropriate than the role of the player.
Maybe it sounds weird, because we had a good time, we win well and we had a few successful moments.
But it's hard to be a player.
You have to do a lot of things and repeat them weekly.
I face similar situations as a manager, with regard to stress and pressure, but I feel that it is the right role for me.
I've always wanted to be a manager and now, that I can do this, I feel that it's the thing that fits me best in my entire adult life."
