Earthquakes and tsunamis in Indonesia
At least 384 people died because of a strong earthquake and tsunami that struck the Indonesian city of Palu on Friday, and it is expected that the number of deaths will increase.
Due to the disruption of communications networks, the disaster authorities were unable to obtain any information from the Donggala Regency, an area in the north of Palu, which is closer to the epicenter of the earthquake with a magnitude of 7.5 degrees on the Richter scale.
In Palu, more than 16,000 people were evacuated after the disaster.
Here are some key information about Palu and Donggala, on the island of Sulawesi:
Palu is the capital of the province of central Sulawesi, which is located at the end of a narrow golf course, on the western coast of the island Sulawesi, with a population of approximately 379,800 in 2017.
The city celebrated 40 years of existence when it was hit by tsunami and earthquake.
Donggala is a regency that stretches along a coast with an area of more than 300 km north-west of Sulawesi Island.
The Region, an administrative region below a province, has a population of approximately 299,200 in 2017.
Fishing and farming activities represent the central point of the economy of the province of the center of the island of Sulawesi, in particular of the Donggala coastal region.
Mining activities for nickel extraction are also important in the province, but are mainly concentrated in the Morowali on the opposite coast of the island of Sulawesi.
Palu and Donggala have been hit several times in the last 100 years, according to the Indonesian Disaster Management Agency.
In 1938, a tsunami caused the death of more than 200 people and destroyed hundreds of homes in Donggala.
Also, in 1996, a tsunami struck the western part of the Donggala regime, causing the death of nine people.
Indonesia is located in the Pacific Fire Circle, an area with intense seismic activity.
Here are some of the earthquakes and tsunamis that have occurred in recent years:
2004: on 26 December, a strong earthquake on the west coast of the Indonesian province of Aceh, north of Sumatra, triggered a tsunami that struck 14 countries, causing the death of 226,000 people on the coast of the Indian Ocean, more than half of them from Aceh.
2005: A series of powerful earthquakes struck the west coast of Sumatra at the end of March and early April.
Hundreds of people died on Nias Island off the coast of Sumatra.
2006: a 6.8-degree magnitude earthquake on Richter scale struck the southernmost Indonesian island, Java, triggering a tsunami that hit the southern coast, killing nearly 700 people.
2009: a 7.6-degree magnitude earthquake on the Richter scale took place near the city of Padang, the capital of the province of Western Sumatra.
