How can the trade war between the United States and China be beneficial for Beijing?
The salves that announced the beginning of the trade war between the United States and China were absurd and, although there seems to be a long way to end it, the disputes between the two countries could be beneficial for Beijing in the long run, experts say.
Donald Trump, President of the United States, issued the first warning earlier this year, by imposing taxes on key imports from China, including solar panels, steel and aluminium.
The most important escalation occurred this week with new taxes, which affected products worth $200 billion (150 billion pounds), effectively applying taxes for half of all Chinese goods arriving in the United States.
Beijing has avenged itself each time, most recently imposing a tax of between 5 and 10 per cent on US products worth 60 billion dollars.
China has warned that it will respond to every blow from the United States and it is unlikely that the world's second largest economy will take a step back in the near future.
For Washington to withdraw, China must agree with its demands, but public surrender to the United States would be too humiliating for Xi Jinping, China's president.
However, experts say that if Beijing plays its cards well, the pressure of the United States on the trade war could support China positively in the long term, reducing the interdependence of the two economies.
"The fact that a rapid political decision taken in Washington or Beijing could lead to an economic collapse in both countries would actually be more dangerous than expected so far," said Abigail Grace, an associate researcher focusing on Asia at the Center for a New American Security, a group of experts.
