News about the red tide: concentrations decreased in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
The latest report of the Florida Wildlife Protection Commission shows a general decrease in the concentrations of the Red Sea for certain areas of the Tampa Gulf.
According to the Commission, non-uniform inflorescence conditions are reported in the areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier – suggesting lower concentrations.
This red sea inflorescence extends over an area of the coast of approximately 210 km, north of Pinellas County to the south of Lee County.
The stains can be found approximately 16 km away from Hillsborough County, but in less places than last week.
The red tide was also observed in Pasco County.
The average concentrations found in or off Pinellas County were reported last week, as well as low to high concentrations in Hillsborough County, bottom to high concentrations in Manatee County, bottom to high concentrations in Sarasota County or across it, bottom to middle concentrations in Charlotte County, bottom to high concentrations in Lee County and across it and low concentrations in Collier County.
Respiratory irritations in Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier committees continue to be reported.
No cases of irritation of the airways have been reported in the northwest of the American state of Florida in the last week.
